To calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons with a wavelength of 300 nm, the formula for photon energy is used, considering one mole of photons. The energy per mole in kJ/mol is given by \( E = \frac{hcN_A}{\lambda} \times \frac{1}{1000} \), where \( h \) is Planck's constant (\( 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s} \)), \( c \) is the speed of light (\( 3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \)), \( N_A \) is Avogadro's number (\( 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1} \)), and \( \lambda \) is the wavelength in meters.

Convert the wavelength to meters: \( \lambda = 300 \, \text{nm} = 300 \times 10^{-9} \, \text{m} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} \).

First, calculate the energy for one photon:
\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{hc}{\lambda} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = \frac{1.9878 \times 10^{-25}}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J}.
\]

Then, calculate for one mole:
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = E_{\text{photon}} \times N_A = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}.
\]

Convert to kJ/mol:
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399.0 \, \text{kJ/mol}.
\]

Considering significant figures (the wavelength 300 nm has three significant figures), the result is rounded to 399 kJ/mol.

The typical single-bond energy is 400 kJ/mol. The photon energy (399 kJ/mol) is very close to this bond energy, indicating that UV photons of this wavelength can break typical single bonds.

